user account information is stored in /etc/passwd, but passwords are hashed stored in another file /etc/shadow.
group information is stored in /etc/group
$ grep -i ^bob /etc/passwd
bob:x:1001:1001::/home/bob:/bin/bash            //output format: USERNAME:PASSWORD:UID:GID:GECOS:HOMEDIR:SHELL  
//PASSWORD: value x menas that it's stored in shadow file
//GECOS is a csv format or comma seperated list of user info, optional field

$ grep -i ^bob /etc/shadow          
bob:fkdgk435294^%&(*^&Sfkjgsdk;fg3495238/7.kdfgsk&^&^&dkfhsdklf:18188:0:99999:7:::    //output format: USERNAME:PASSWORD:LASTCHANGE:MINAGE:MAXAGE:WARN:INACTIVE:EXPDATE
//LASTCHANGE: the date since the password was last changed, shows number of dates since 00.00.00 UTC 01/01/1970 (Unix Epoch)
//MINAGE: min days the user has to wait to be able to change the password
//MAXAGE: max days the user has to change password
//WARN: the nubmer of days before a password is going to expire that the user should be warned so they can change it
//INACTIVE: the number of days a password has expired that it should still be accepted before being disabled, optional
//EXPDATE: Epoch, optional, no value means never expires

$ id                           //provides information of the user
$ who                          //shows who are currently logged in 
$ last                         //shows records of all logged in users

switch users with 'sudo':
only users in /etc/soduers can use 'sudo', and this file can be edited with 'visudo' command.
set up a nologin shell, so no one can login as a root user directly:
$ grep -i ^root /etc/passwd

commands:
as a root user:
$ useradd bob          //add user bob
$ passwd bob           //set password for bob
$ userdel bob
as bob:
$ whoami
$ passwd              //set password
perform groups:
$ groupadd -g 1011 groupname        //customise group id as 1011
$ groupdel groupname

ls command:
$ ls -ld /home/bob/filename
d--xrwxrwx 1 bob bob 89 Mar 17 01:35 .    //--x is permission of file owner, rwx is permission of owner's group, next rwx is permission of any other person
//x is execute permission, which允许bob把文件当程序执行
//here owner doesnt have read access to the file, and his group does, in this case owner still cant inherit the permissions from the group because Linux read permissions sequentially,
//so other people in the same group would inherit group permissions regardless of what permissions they are assigned.

modify permissions:
$ chmod ug+r-x filename        //add r-x to user and group 
$ chmod o-w filename         //remove rwx from others 
alternatively: rwx is 421
$ chmod 660 filename           //add rw- to user and group, remove all permissions from others

change owner for the file:
$ chown bob:groupname filename
$ chown bob filename
$ chgrp groupname filename
$ sudo chown -R mercury /home/bob/sports            //change owner of the folder sports and recursively the files under it by using -R  (has to be capital, -r doesnt work)
